It has a living room to the left upon walking in the front door and overall had a pretty "open-floor" layout. When I was in 6th grade, my parents had made their intentions very clear that they wanted me to go to a private middle school. I did not want to do this as I had all my friends at my current school and was happy where I was. I made this very clear to them, but they still went around researching different private schools for me to go to. Once again, I voiced my opinion but they did not listen to me. I felt ignored, and that made me incredibly angry. I let them know that I felt that I should have a greater input into where I choose to go to school, as it is my life. However, they did not listen to me. Instead, they told me that we were going to an open house later that night at the school that they liked the most. My stomach turned in that moment because I did not know what I would be able to do without my friends. Later that night, we went to the open house. The school was centered in some dilapidated office buildings in the suburbs of the city, and I immediately grew to dislike them. We walked into the cafeteria, where they were holding the open house, and it smelled like old food. I'm not sure why I remember that specific aspect, but it does help reflect my sentiment towards this situation as a whole. I barely listened to anything that the president of the school said as 
a protest towards my parents' lack of hearing out my issues. The open house ended, and I was as underwhelmed as I was before we arrived. During my senior year of high school my track team was going into the state track meet not expecting much, but rather excited to participate. The state championship came down to the very last race because of how tight the scores were and our team had to do well in order to win the overall title. It wasn't that we had forgotten what had happened or what we would have to face after we left the concert, but that we were able to put our attention on what was happening around us and on each other. I felt angry when I had an argument with my best friend from home over thanksgiving break. We fought this summer and our friendship has been impacted since then. We are not the same in the way we approach each other and behave around each other. We tend to hold back and not be real with each other. This made me angry and we had an argument about it over break. We wern't aggressive but rather were sad about the situation. We are both extremely passionate individuals and we deal with conflict passionately. 

We were dancing at a club in San Diego and got into an argument. We both blame each other and hold each other responsible .for our friendship not being the same anymore. That is probably why we are angry at each other. More than anything else, we are passive aggressive towards one another. My emotions are severely impacted by this whole situation given that I am a very sensitive person. I tend to be extremely sensitive in situations as such and that makes me overthink. With this particular event, I think I just overthought throughout and felt like I needed to change who I am to make my friend feel more comfortable around me. That is not how we both see our friendship and the fact that we confronted each other in the summer has made us more wary around each other. 

At this point, I feel extremely sad and confused because I do not know whether I can regain the friendship that I once shared with this friend and whether I will be able to pick back up with her from where I once was. I am worried that this event could have changed the dynamic of our friendship. I have also realized the circumstantial nature of friendships and relationships. Things change based on environment and now that I am at college, and not back home in New Delhi, my dynamic with this individual has changed significantly. It is always hard to recognize change and accept it. Change is scary and unpredictable and makes you feel a lack of security. That is the overarching emotion that I feel at this point because I am not secure in the status of our friendship and neither is my friend. There is no point in constantly bringing up instances from the past and attempting to salvage a friendship if the same argument continues to repeat itself. I need to realize that and act accordingly. 

I think I am at a stage in life where I am more self-aware and confident in my decision making. I think I know better than I did at one point in life

I lived in a house called the Lola Place. It was reminiscent of the color purple. In the living room mirrors covered the entire wall on the right side and there was wood paneling on the floor. There was a LaZ boy recliner and a couch, both of which faced a tv. Behind it was a coffee table we often did puzzles at. To the left was the kitchen and further in was the dining room table. Just behind the dining room table was a sliding glass door that led to a patio with a jacuzzi that no longer functioned as well as a laundry room. Then past the patio was dirt and vines and an old car that belonged to my uncle. Back inside the house in front of the dining room was my moms small office, with just a chair and a desk. All the way at the end of the hallway was my room, with purple and green painted walls. There was a blue bookcase next to my closet with all my favorite books in it and then my bed next to it with a spring themed comforter atop it. Next to my bedroom was a bathroom, and next to that was my moms room. She had a king sized water bed that filled up most of the room. She also had a tiny closet. Out in the backyard again, there were many stuffed animals that my dog, Radar buried, with only their heads above the ground. Right next to the gate was a hay bale and further around the back was a shed that I never went in. On the opposite side of the yard was a bundle of rose bushes, which immediately died whenever winter came around yet they somehow always came back to life afterwards. The front yard had gravel in it, and we lived on a culdesac.

How happy I felt during a particular event really depends on how low my emotions were before that event occurred. The immediate event that pops into mind is last winter, when amidst snow and flurries I was out late at night drinking cocktails with my high school friends. The reason this memory is the first to be recalled, though, mostly has to do with the fact that college social life is pretty boring and I miss being able to go out to bars without worrying about age restrictions. I also have low tolerance for heat, so after Fall semester when the heat gets semi-unbearable the coolness of South Korean winter is such a welcome change. Just to provide more detail, I had planned to meet my best friend from high school months before I went back to Korea for winter break, and had woken up that day already excited. I dressed in the best clothes I had at the moment - a black open shoulder shirt with long tight pants - and met with my friend at Hong Dae Street, one of the go-to places for young adults to play in South Korea. We met around 12pm, just in time for lunch, and spent two hours eating and catching up. We then mostly scoured the streets, going into a VR game station and competing in fake horse back riding (since both of us had done horse back riding in high school), buying earrings and snacking on various juices and ice creams. Around dinner time we had a quick bite of spicy rice cakes and proceeded to walk towards Hap Jeong Station, near which are various high-quality bars. I don't quite remember what drinks we had (but have it written down in my phone) but I do remember we ordered an array of sausages after our first drink and ended up loving it. I have lived in the same house my entire life. My parents bought the house after I was born, and this is the only house I have ever known. I will probably remember the address for the rest of my life: 2827 Evergreen Point road, Medina Washington. Medina is a quaint neighborhood with well-kept lawns and iron gates. When you turn down the long driveway, the large yellow house stares back at you. The inviting green lawn hug the edges. As you walk inside you feel cozy. There is a staircase at the entrance, and the living room has fluffy couches and a sculpture that is apparently made by some famous artist that no one has heard of. Next we go to the sunroom, which gets its name because the majority of the walls are floor to ceiling windows. The room would be flooded with light in most places, but in Seattle it usually has pounding rain and streaks of water running down. Some people find it gloomy but I find it therapeutic. Next is the dining room. There is not much to see here, and we rarely go in there except for holidays or when family is over. Baby photos and my mom's collection of small glass animal figurines line the shelf. In the kitchen, my mom is usually alive with activity. This is the casual place where we all enjoy spending time together, plus nothing brings my family together like food does. Now we move to the upstairs, where the kids rooms are and my parents room. My room is quite interesting. When my parents first bought the house, the room used to be a storage closet. I suppose when I was born, my grandfather decided that the existing rooms were not fitting enough for me and knocked out the walls to create a larger room. The walls are very low and sloped, which is a very odd sight considering I am six foot two

A time in my life where I was extremely happy took place about 3 and a half years ago, when I met my niece for the first time. My brother and his wife live in Bainbridge Island, and I live in San Francisco, so I didn't get a chance to meet her when she was born. However, their first visit with her took place several months after she was born. I remember seeing her for the first time so vividly, and I loved her from that moment on. My three brothers, sister in law, parents, and dog were all there completely focused on the tiny baby in my brother's arms. She had on a pink onesie and immediately after taking her into my arms she fell asleep. She was the most precious and delicate human I had ever seen, much less held. Although she was too young to talk, she seemed to communicate non-verbally in a way that everyone understood. Her bright blue eyes held mine for what seemed like an hour, but was probably no more than five minutes. Within 30 seconds she had absolutely stolen the hearts of everyone in the room, and we all loved her instantly. After waking up in my arms about 15 minutes after falling asleep, she started smiling. It was amazing, she didn't cry or squirm, but seemed perfectly content with a complete stranger. After that day, I would have done anything for her. I was amazed by this tiny human that shared my blood, that my brother had created. After all the obstacles my sister in law had endured throughout her pregnancy, they had the most perfect baby I had ever seen. It all seemed so worth it, and I felt as though this one event had brought us all closer through none of our doing.
